<ROW><CELL><foreign lang=la>Prebens solamen : viduis egris medicamen. Anno milleno : ter C quarto nonageno, Junii septeno : mensis migravit ameno.</foreign></CELL></ROW>

</TABLE>
 
<div2 type=section id="c.2.8"><HEAD>Brass of John Waltham, Bishop of Salisbury.</HEAD>
 
<p>On the floor in this chapel is a slab with a brass figure of John Waltham, bishop of Salisbury, who died <datestruct value="1395--"><year reg="1395">1395</year></datestruct>, it is richly attired in pontificals under a handsome canopy, with saints with their names in brass, of which only remain the following:-- 
<p>On the north side, St. John the Evangelist, with the chalice and dragon. 
<QUOTE rend=center>Johes Evan.</QUOTE>
 
<p>St. John of Beverley, pontifically habited. 
<QUOTE rend=center>S&lsquo; Johes Belvair.</QUOTE>
 
<p>St. John, Almoner, habited as a pilgrim, with a loaf of bread and a pilgrim's staff. 
<QUOTE rend=center>St. Johes Clemosiner.</QUOTE>
 
<pb id="p.67" n="67">
 
<p>At the foot of Richard II. stands a small insignificant tomb, hardly <num value="3">three</num> feet square, and not more than that high, and which contains the ashes of Margaret, daughter to Edward IV. 
<p><FIGURE id="Fig.067"><HEAD>Sword and Shield of Edward III.</HEAD></FIGURE>
<p>The long iron rusty sword of Edward III. and the wooden part of his shield, broken and patched, rest on the above tomb. The dimensions of the sword are as follows:-- 
